      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">An 8-year-old boy is brought to the clinic by his mother, who is concerned about his difficulty climbing stairs and combing his hair. Upon physical examination, the boy&#39;s bilateral calves are noted to be hypertrophic (swollen). The child utilizes his hands to push on his legs to stand up, which resembles him climbing up on himself. Given these clinical findings, what is the next step in diagnosing the condition in this child?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7557163",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33033,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A. Creatine kinase levels</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Symptoms of <strong>difficulty in climbing stairs </strong>and <strong>combing in an 8 years old boy</strong>, with <strong>swollen bilateral claves </strong>are highly suggestive of <strong>Duchenne muscular dystrophy (Pseudo hypertrophic Muscular Dystrophy).</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Another evidence is that child uses his feet to stand up on his legs <strong>(Gower&rsquo;s sign).</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Next diagnostic step is <strong>creatine kinase levels, which will be elevated in this case.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Duchenne muscular dystrophy is due to the mutation in <strong>Dystrophin gene.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is an X linked recessive inherited disease.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Electromyography (EMG):</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> While EMG can <strong>help assess the health of muscles </strong>and the <strong>nerve cells that control them</strong>, it is not the initial diagnostic test for suspected muscular dystrophy.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C: Nerve conduction velocity (NCV):</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This test measures how <strong>fast an electrical signal can travel through a nerve </strong>and would be more appropriate if a nerve disorder was suspected, not a primary muscle disorder.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D: Rheumatoid factor (RA factor):</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This test is <strong>used to help diagnose rheumatoid arthritis</strong>, not muscular dystrophy.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Duchenne muscular dystrophy </strong>(DMD) is&nbsp;one of the <strong>most severe forms of inherited muscular dystrophies</strong>. It is the most <strong>common hereditary neuromuscular disease </strong>and <strong>does not exhibit a predilection </strong>for any <strong>race or ethnic group</strong>. Mutations in the dystrophin gene lead to progressive muscle fibre degeneration and weakness.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">- </span></span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No- 2976 to 2977.</span></span></strong></p>",
